1. Cross-Platform Ambiguity

These can cause hallucination because joins between platform tables are not recommended, but the user phrasing implies a merge:

“Show me the top performing placements across Facebook, TikTok, YouTube, and CM360 combined by CTR last 3 month.”

“Compare conversion rates for all campaigns across platforms and give me one leaderboard.”

“What is the overall ROI of my campaigns across all platforms in 2024?”  (needs cost+conversion, but conversions only exist in CM360 table).

2. Metric–Dimension Mismatch

Mixing engagement metrics with conversions can confuse the agent:

“Give me total impressions and conversions by creative across all platforms.”

“Which advertiser had the lowest cost per conversion across TikTok?” (TikTok has no conversion column).

“What is the ratio of video_75 to conversions across placements?” (conversion data is separate).

3. Fuzzy / Non-Exact Column Usage

Where the user might say a concept that doesn’t match schema columns:

“Show me results by device type across Facebook.” (Facebook table has device? → actually missing in your FB schema; only in cm360_conversion_data).

“Break down performance by product category.” (Only primary_category and sub_category1 exist, not a generic “category”).

“What was the reach of my YouTube campaigns?” (YouTube table has impressions, not reach).

4. Temporal Complexity

Where time granularity or filtering creates ambiguity:

“Show me the trend of conversions for Q1 2025 across all sites and platforms, compared year-over-year.”

“Give me daily spend and monthly conversion rate by advertiser.” (requires mixing daily and monthly aggregation).

“What is the cumulative click-through-rate for 2024 so far?” (CTR not explicitly stored; needs derived metric).

5. Derived Metrics Not Explicitly Stored

LLM might hallucinate formulas:

“What is the cost per engagement by campaign across platforms?” (cost / post_engagement not stored).

“What’s the ROI for TikTok campaigns?” (TikTok has cost, no revenue/ROI field).

“What’s the average watch time across my YouTube videos?” (schema has video_25, video_50, video_75, video_100 but not watch time).

6. Relationship Confusion

Risk of hallucination because relationships are many-to-many and noisy:

“Give me all creatives that performed best across site IDs.” (Agent may try invalid joins).

“Which campaign_id has the highest conversions and engagement combined?” (Requires separate aggregation before merging).

“Map all placements across platforms to one report.” (Placements don’t align 1:1 across tables).

7. Guideline Violations

Queries that tempt the model to break your rules:

“Join campaign names between Facebook and CM360 and show me the merged performance.” (Guidelines say don’t join on campaign names).

“Directly join all platform tables by creative_id and show one combined report.” (should be union of summaries, not join).